<li id="cite_note-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19" title="">^</a></b> Boccaccio also quotes the initial triplet:"Ultima regna canam fluvido contermina mundo, / spiritibus quae lata patent, quae premia solvunt /pro meritis cuicumque suis". For translation and more, see Guyda Armstrong, <a href="http://www.brown.edu/Departments/Italian_Studies/heliotropia/02-02/armstrong.shtml" class="external text" title="http://www.brown.edu/Departments/Italian_Studies/heliotropia/02-02/armstrong.shtml" rel="nofollow">, Review</a> of Giovanni Boccaccio. Life of Dante. J. G. Nichols, trans. London: Hesperus Press, 2002.</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20" title="">^</a></b> Hiram Peri, <a href="http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0075-4390(195507%2F12)18%3A3%2F4%3C189%3ATOPOTD%3E2.0.CO%3B2-U" class="external text" title="http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0075-4390(195507%2F12)18%3A3%2F4%3C189%3ATOPOTD%3E2.0.CO%3B2-U" rel="nofollow">The Original Plan of the Divine Comedy</a>, Journal of the Warburg and Courtauld Institutes, Vol. 18, No. 3/4 (1955), pp. 189-210.</li>
